Gunsmith/Colin Wallis.
      You can't be good at everything. You always have to sacrifice efficiency. This simple truth Colin had learned a long time ago. For someone this rule was less fair, for someone — more. And in his case, that rule treated him with all its effective cruelty.
      The armorer was well aware that he was a good Technician. One of the hero's few disciples, a member of the first guard, one of the key members of the Protectorate... People could say a lot about him as a Cape, but almost no one could say anything about him as a person. And Colin couldn't blame them.
      He was well aware of how narrow his social interactions were, and how weak he was in what people called "empathy." He tried to compensate for these shortcomings through the use of their abilities — so there was his visor with built-in lie detector and analyzer of social ties. But even so, he was far from being a normal person. And he was quite willing to sacrifice the effectiveness of his "I" for the sake of his heroic role. But not always this efficiency came to his hand, and he could not but admit it. So it happened now.
      His software for predicting social behavior again showed its imperfection, not allowing him to draw the necessary conclusions. The Director did not mention what was written in Ebert's diary, and Colin had drawn the wrong conclusions. It was simple. An error in the calculations leading to a decrease in efficiency to critical levels.
      And now he needs as quickly as possible to neutralize the cause of these disturbances, while the whole system is not rolled downhill, completely losing all efficiency.
      An outsider, if he knew in any form what categories the protectorate hero thought, would be shocked, but for the Technician himself it was just a simple mental trick that allowed him to interact with reality and society at an acceptable level — he only perceived reality as tinkertech.
      Suddenly, a light chime sounded from the speakers of his helmet, signaling the request for an incoming connection. Displaying the helmet's caller ID, the Gunsmith immediately accepted the call.
      — Dragon, I was given direct access to communication systems? Why don't you use this?
      — My father always taught me to knock before I came in. Just good manners. Hi, Colin.
       Hello... Dragon, is a canadian Nerd, a mysterious girl with agoraphobia, was probably the only person in the understanding of Colin approached the meaning of the word "friend."
      Their communication was... productive. The dragon is very much helped Colin in his technarte, they also work together to develop some projects that could help not only "Guild" and the protectorate, but generally around the world. Therefore, in her presence, if you could call "presence" audiovisual two-way communication channels, he allowed himself to be a little more... ineffective, if they were not busy with any work. That, however, happened rarely.
      — I... I heard what happened. I feel so sorry for these people... Colin, it's not your fault. Piggot admitted it herself.
      Colin shook his head.
      — I was wrong.
      — We're all wrong, Colin. All of us. But we have to learn from our mistakes?
      There was a brief silence as the Armorer headed toward his workshop. Before he went inside, he sighed to answer his partner... and friend.
       It's effective. Will you help me find the Ghost Stalker?
       Sure, Colin. Getting access to security cameras all over the city. If she catches a glimpse of at least one — I know.
       Thanks, Dragon.

